{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"fd0f5bbd-0684-4d90-9ce6-90da308af993","content":"Here's what you need:\n\n### 1. `Directory.Build.props` (at solution root, for consistency)\n\n```xml\n<Project>\n  <PropertyGroup>\n    <EnableMSTestRunner>true</EnableMSTestRunner>\n    <OutputType>Exe</OutputType>\n    <TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport>true</TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport>\n  </PropertyGroup>\n</Project>\n```\n\n- **`EnableMSTestRunner`** — switches from VSTest to Microsoft.Testing.Platform (built into MSTest 3.4+).\n- **`OutputType Exe`** — required because each test project now produces a self-contained test host executable.\n- **`TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport`** — lets `dotnet test` delegate to the new platform (needed on .NET 8 SDK).\n\n### 2. Add the TRX extension to each test `.csproj`\n\nThe VSTest `--logger trx` flag doesn't carry over. Install the dedicated package in each test project:\n\n```xml\n<PackageReference Include=\"Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.TrxReport\" Version=\"1.*\" />\n```\n\n### 3. CI command\n\n```diff\n- dotnet test --logger trx\n+ dotnet test -- --report-trx\n```\n\nEverything after `--` is forwarded to the Microsoft.Testing.Platform host. `--report-trx` activates the TRX report extension and writes `.trx` files to the `TestResults/` folder, same as before.\n\n### Summary of per-project changes\n\n| Where | What |\n|---|---|\n| `Directory.Build.props` | 3 properties (shared) |\n| Each test `.csproj` | Add `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.TrxReport` package |\n| CI script | `dotnet test -- --report-trx` |\n\nNo other package or code changes are needed — MSTest 3.8.0 already bundles the platform runner.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"4e852349-bf73-4bb9-a3be-727f1766fcba","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user wants to migrate their MSTest 3.8.0 test projects from VSTest to Microsoft.Testing.Platform. Let me provide a clear, concise answer based on my knowledge of this migration path.\n\nKey changes needed:\n\n1. **Project-level change**: Add `<EnableMSTestRunner>true</EnableMSTestRunner>` and `<OutputType>Exe</OutputType>` to each test project, or better yet, use a `Directory.Build.props` to set it consistently.\n\n2. **For MSTest 3.8.0**: The `Microsoft.Testing.Platform` integration is available. With MSTest 3.4+, you can enable the MSTest runner.\n\n\n3. **CI command change**: `dotnet test` still works, but the logger syntax changes with Microsoft.Testing.Platform. You'll need the `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.TrxReport` NuGet package to generate TRX reports in the new runner. Configuring the testing platform properties...","outputTokens":1294,"requestId":"4820:3932DE:3245B16:36CF011:69FBE1D3"},"id":"d0564227-e2df-4dfa-8bf2-e9239ad55b4d","timestamp":"2026-05-07T00:50:50.857Z","parentId":"96d9dc8d-b3eb-468a-bd43-9e7213754086"}
